# ui-context-menu

## Slot-based Item Templates

Place a `<template slot="item">` inside the menu to customize how each option renders. The slot receives scoped bindings via `let-item`, `let-index`, `let-level`, `let-path`, `let-active`, `let-checked`, and `let-has-children`, so you can render badges, descriptions, icons, or contextual helpers alongside the default fallback markup.

```html
<ui-context-menu ... visible-count="5">
  <template slot="item" let-item let-index let-level let-active>
    <div class="hero-item">
      <span class="index">{index + 1}</span>
      <strong>{item.label}</strong>
      <small>Level {level + 1}</small>
    </div>
  </template>
</ui-context-menu>
```

Use the `reserveIconSpace` prop to keep the icon column intact even when your template omits it, keeping virtualized windows aligned with default themes.

## Virtualization & Async Item Loading

Enable virtualization by setting `visible-count` to a positive number and specifying the per-item `item-height` so the component can calculate scroll windows. The menu renders only the visible slice and uses deterministic `item-height` math to offset the caret.

Provide a `loadItems(offset, limit)` callback when you have a large dataset or want server-paged results. The component calls this async loader as the user scrolls near the window’s edge and appends the returned items to the list. The example below throttles fetches while `visible-count` stays at 5:

```tsx
menu.visibleCount = 5;
menu.itemHeight = 44;
menu.loadItems = async (offset, limit) => {
  const page = await fetch(`/api/actions?skip=${offset}&limit=${limit}`);
  return page.json();
};
```

The fallback behavior is to render the full list when no virtualization props are provided, preserving the classic context-menu look.

## Lifecycle Hooks

Use `beforeOpen`/`beforeClose` to gate the menu toggle. Returning `false` or rejecting a promise cancels the transition while resolving an async promise delays it until the promise settles.

```tsx
menu.beforeClose = () => {
  indicator.textContent = 'Saving…';
  return new Promise((resolve) => setTimeout(() => {
    indicator.textContent = 'Saved';
    resolve(true);
  }, 600));
};
```

These hooks mirror traditional `contextmenu` events but allow you to persist state, flush analytics, or show ephemeral feedback before the menu appears or disappears.

